Statistics.setVarianceImpl makes getStandardDeviation produce NaN
Invoking SummaryStatistics.setVarianceImpl(new Variance(true/false) makes getStandardDeviation produce NaN. The code to reproduce it:  int[] scores = {1, 2, 3, 4}; SummaryStatistics stats = new SummaryStatistics(); stats.setVarianceImpl(new Variance(false)); //use "population variance" for(int i : scores) {   stats.addValue(i); } double sd = stats.getStandardDeviation(); System.out.println(sd);   A workaround suggested by Mikkel is:    double sd = FastMath.sqrt(stats.getSecondMoment() / stats.getN());  